Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text: Located at 1550 Lamar Street, the building is designed by the internationally renowned Bjarke Ingels Group (BIG) and earns the distinguishment as their first project in Texas. The building features a distinctive side core design and cantilevered structure allowing for panoramic views of the park and abundant natural light. Additionally, it features unique rooftop terraces comprised of local flora producing a suburban feel in an urban environment.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
Breaking ground in June of 2021, 1550 on the Green is the newest addition to Houston’s CBD skyline. The 28-story, 375,000-square-foot project is the beginning of yet another remarkable endeavor by Skanska in downtown Houston. The project, directly adjacent to the park at Discovery Green, is the first phase of a three-block, master-planned district Skanska is developing as Discovery West. 

In conjunction with BIG, the Austin-based Michael Hsu Office of Architecture is tasked with the interiors of the project. The building is anchored at the ground level with 7,000 SF of retail and an overextended 5,000 SF of outdoor patio dining. Additionally, it will host a spa-like fitness center, tenant lounge and luxurious locker rooms overlooking the park. Topping off the building on the 28th floor is an exclusive 9,000 SF conferencing center and rooftop lounge alongside a 5,000 SF outdoor terrace overlooking the park. 

As a forward-thinking leader in the business, Skanska places a heavy focus on sustainability and tenant wellness with its pursuit of multiple designations: WELL
Building Standard – Platinum, LEED Platinum V4 for both core and shell, Fitwell 3-of-3-Star Rating, and Energy Star Rating. With an expected completion in
late-2023, 1550 on the Green is currently 32 percent pre-leased and will represent the pinnacle in health wellness of the office marketplace upon delivery.
The carefully curated design and tenant-mindedness of 1550 on the Green is reshaping how we think of the office – giving people a reason to come to work.

Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text: Centrally located in the Central Business District and close to Pennzoil Place, Shell Plaza, Bank of America Center and JP Morgan Chase Tower, this building features polished granite panels extending from the first through the fourth floors to form the base of the building’s exterior, with a dramatic metal panel curtain wall made of satin-finish aluminum, rising from the fifth through the penthouse levels.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
The Building is centrally located on the downtown tunnel system and contains the only “true hub” that allows underground access in all directions.  There are over 30 food and beverage operations located within a two-block radius of the Building.  A full-service bank, document services firm, investment brokerage office and dentist are located on the Lobby Level.  The Building’s Tunnel Level offers various restaurants, medical offices, a sundry and gift shop and a photograph services shop.  Postal service and overnight express drop boxes are also available on the Tunnel Level. 

The building underwent a $27 million renovation in 1992-1994, which included the modernization of the exterior surfaces, interior public areas and mechanical systems.  In 2000, the building lighting system was retrofitted from conventional lamps to energy-efficient lamps with electronic ballasts.  Under new ownership, in 2006, the building was renovated to include a four-level parking facility located within the Building

A separate structure built atop the fourth floor is connected to the tower by an enclosed glass walkway that leads to the legendary Coronado Club.

Common.Strapline.Common.Text: Making Business a Part of History

Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text: TC Energy Center is a 56 story office tower located at 700 Louisiana Street in downtown Houston. The building encompasses 1.25 million square feet of office and retail space and is linked to the extensive Downtown Houston tunnel system.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text:
Among the most well known architects in the United States, Philip Johnson and John Burgee have created distinctive structures in most of this country's major cities. TC Energy Center’s original design strikes a synthesis of past and present. 

The interior and exterior of the building is sheathed in rough textured Napoleon red granite, quarried in Sweden and finished in Italy. Even the surrounding sidewalks are composed of the same granite used in the building. The lobby is highlighted by an 18 foot high 1914 Seth Thomas clock, of which only 300 were ever built. The entrance from Louisiana Street is an impressive seventy-five foot high, arched granite doorway. The granite stonework soars upward to 102 feet, 10 stories, and is so intricate that specialists from Spain were brought to Houston to install the more than 100 pieces around the arch. This archway continues through the center of the building to a second arched doorway that opens onto Smith Street. As an added feature, three of the lower office tower floors are bisected by the archway and connected by pedestrian bridges.

In addition to its proximity to numerous restaurants, hotels and other Theatre District entertainment venues, the Building offers the following on-site amenities: Coffee Bar Proudly Serving Starbucks, Murphy’s Deli, Glamour Newsstand and Sundry Shop (all under the Building). The Lancaster Hotel is located two blocks to the NE of the Building. In addition to the above, the Landlord has completed Phase I of its extensive renovation program to create a full-service restaurant space that is located on the ground floor of the former Western Union building in the NW corner of the Building lobby.

Phase II of additional renovations and dramatic improvements to the banking hall are underway. The improvements will include the installation of a coffee bar, tenant lounge and tenant conference center on the ground floor in the former bank lobby. Full height windows on the Rusk Street side and punched in windows on the Louisiana Street side will bring significant natural light into the Lobby. Two half-floor mezzanine levels with glass fronts will be added for creative office space. 

A fitness center for tenants of the Building is being constructed on the second floor of the Western Union building with direct elevator service from the lobby. The fitness center will include full state of the art equipment, locker rooms with showers and towel service.

Destination dispatch elevators using the Otis Compass Plus system are being installed in each office elevator bank for added efficiency and energy savings. 

Lynn Wyatt Square for the Performing Arts (formerly named Jones Plaza) has planned improvements to become a more visitor friendly outdoor green space. This block will be activated with a restaurant and additional entertainment areas.

Conferencing center; Tunnel connected with excellent amenities; The Health Club at Travis Place; Convenient access to Coronado, Petroleum and Houston Clubs; Ready access to multiple Metro bus stops; On-site property management

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text: Autry Park will feature two Class A office towers in the center of this emerging district. Phase I office has a modern, architecturally unique sustainable design based on natural light and cross-laminated timber (CLT) that create a striking urban scale office with street and park connection. The building will be a luxury boutique offering that is constructed of a CLT Hybrid structural system (the structural frame is steel and the floor/ceiling deck material is cross laminated timber, CLT). The CLT deck creates a very appealing wood soffit finish in each lease space. A great alternative to downtown, Autry Park is part of a 14 acre mixed use campus offering restaurants, fitness luxury multifamily housing and greenspace amenities with a new stoplight anchored intersection directly into Buffalo Bayou Park. The initial mixed use components of high-rise and garden style residential structures are scheduled for completion in Q4 2021 while the initial retail and restaurant components are scheduled for Q1 2022 completion.
